  <text>
     <body>
     <div type="poem">
   <lg>
      <pb facs="9"/>
      <l>THou sole companion of our oft chang'd State,</l>
      <l>Sprong from the bowels of this sea-wald Ile:</l>
      <l>Whom al-deuouring time could not exile,</l>
      <l>So haue we constant beene despite of fate.</l>
      <l>That how soeuer fortune tyrannizde,</l>
      <l>We euer thee with all affections prizde,</l>
   </lg>
   <lg>
      <l>Now since the splendor of a blessed time</l>
      <l>Hath raizd our fortune, wee will reare thy praise</l>
      <l>With Madregals, Sonnettos, Roundelaies;</l>
      <l>And add (Art-graced) Prose to Art-like Rime.</l>
      <l>Thus <hi>Perry</hi> doth in his best graced vaine,</l>
      <l>Where first he breathd, imploying there his paine.</l>
   </lg>
   <lg>
      <l>Praise cannot add more worth, but shewe affection,</l>
      <l>And vertue of it selfe, it selfe doth grace;</l>
      <l>Then cease my pen, lest more, thee more disgrace;</l>
      <l>Since nought thou shew‘st, but thy Arts imperfection:</l>
      <l>Let better wits his labours higher raise,</l>
      <l>Or let them cease, the worke it selfe will praise.</l>
   </lg>
   <p>VVilliam Mathew, Esquire.</p>
</div>
